{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"848247bb-15c7-4501-a524-02172ec7048d","content":"There's no repository content here to reference, so I'll answer from general .NET knowledge:\n\n## Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\nNativeAOT apps don't ship with `createdump` (it's a CoreCLR tool). On macOS, use the OS-level facilities instead:\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — macOS disables them by default:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS places them in `/cores/`):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/    # check for core.XXXX files after a crash\n   ```\n\n3. **If `/cores/` is empty**, macOS may require SIP adjustments or the app must be signed with the `com.apple.security.get-task-allow` entitlement to allow core dumps.\n\n4. **Use `lldb` to analyze the dump**:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.XXXX ./your-nativeaot-app\n   ```\n\n5. **Inside `lldb`**, useful commands:\n   ```\n   bt              # backtrace of the crashing thread\n   thread list     # all threads\n   bt all          # backtraces for every thread\n   register read   # register state\n   ```\n\n6. **Alternative — use macOS Crash Reporter**: Check `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` for `.ips` or `.crash` files generated automatically on crash. These contain symbolic stack traces.\n\n**Key difference from CoreCLR**: Since there's no managed runtime, you won't get managed stack frames — everything is native symbols. Ensure you build with debug symbols (`-p:StripSymbols=false`) to get meaningful backtraces.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"15a017d4-9fda-475d-803c-9627b7765e5c","outputTokens":414,"requestId":"C3D1:2A497:1C7D1B2:201A4A9:6A07C2BA"},"id":"d478fbec-fbbb-42a3-a345-975e2d3c19ad","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:05:09.377Z","parentId":"7dd509ce-6b30-4f75-b136-5a9c5ad7289c"}
